Hackers have breached the database of the Philippine Commission on Elections (COMELEC), exposing the personal information of 55m voters. Hacktivist group, Anonymous, compromised COMELEC’s site on 27 March, following which LulzSec Pilipinas posted the database online. It has been reported that Anonymous was pressing COMELEC to switch on security features in the vote counting machines ahead of elections in May. COMELEC has said that no sensitive information has been compromised, but TrendMicro, which has looked into the matter, disagrees, stating that passport information and fingerprints are among the data. TrendMicro added that voters could now find themselves targeted in a range of schemes from spear-phishing to blackmail. The attack is one of the world’s largest government data breach to date.

The Social Mobility Pledge initiative has found many UK workers believe young people from disadvantaged backgrounds have a tougher time progressing in work than previous generations. The research was commissioned by Conservative MP and former education secretary Justine Greening, founder of the initiative. Greening said the result – 60% of 2,000 people between ages 35 and 64 polled observing the challenges – suggested class differences were less of an obstacle before than now and that diversity was worsening. Around 54% of workers nationally aged 18-64 said advancing as a disadvantaged young person was “difficult”.

Global food services company Sodexo has renewed a revolving credit facility incorporating a sustainability-linked clause. The latest iteration of the €1.3bn deal ties the interest rate on the loan to the company’s pledge to cut food waste and food losses stemming from its operations in half by 2025. Sodexho, its suppliers, clients and consumers are responsible for 117,000 mt of the 1.3 billion mt of global food waste or loss each year, according to CEO Denis Machuel. In May it launched WasteWatch, a data-driven waste prevention programme. Machuel said the amount of food waste is unacceptable both from an environmental and business perspective. Some of the biggest players in the food industry are actively seeking to demonstrate their commitment to improving sustainability of the food chain by tying the interest rate on debt to goals to reduce waste. Leading global commodities traders Louis Dreyfus, Olam and Cofco have also signed sustainability-linked loans tied to their ESG targets and improvement of the traceability of agri-commodities this year.Overall, the sustainability-linked loan sector increased eight fold last year reaching $40bn and banks are being urged to encourage broader adoption. It is clear that corporates are keen extend their ESG efforts beyond issuing green bonds, to fund investment in the necessary infrastructure and technology, to linking the cost of funding day-to-day operations with sustainability goals. In doing so their positive impact on the environment has a similarly positive impact on their financials.

The Greeks were the only ethnic group who granted themselves the moniker Romioi for distinction .
The literate segment of Greeks consider their ethnicity ( genos ) to be Hellenic .
Being classified as Greek was applied by the Ottomans to all members of the Orthodox Church , regardless of their language or ethnic origin .

The Maharashtra State Electricity Distribution Company Ltd (MSEDCL) has issued a tender for the design and manufacture of 7,500 solar water pumps, nine months after it requested tenders for installing 50,000 of the devices. The pumps are destined for farmers across the state, and vendors must include five-year guarantees on the water pumping system and 10-year assurances for the solar modules. MSEDCL said the systems must also support automated meter reading.

As the US continues to undergo major demographic shifts, notably a rapidly aging population, the fundamental shift towards value-based care is becoming one of the most important changes in health care. With shortages of health care providers becoming more prevalent, alternative delivery models must be explored so that the remaining providers can be best utilized. In this landscape, telehealth will come to play a central role. Although long mooted as an alternative, uptake of the technology has remained slow, hindered by several factors. The most commonly acknowledged is reimbursement rates, often owed to inconsistent measurement and mixed results over its efficacy. Academic reviews of telehealth have produced varied results. However, it has been proved to be effective when tackling chronic condition management, remote patient monitoring, and behavioral health. Attempts to bring clarity to telehealth services have been troubled by distinctions in the criteria for assessing its effectiveness, lessening the ability to draw firm conclusions from the research. The most prevalent knowledge gaps are centered around the diverse and limited data regarding costs and utilization, which in turn have come to impact reimbursement rates. To overcome this, there should be a move to establish a standard assessment protocol for telehealth services. To start with, evaluations should focus on the overall impact of a program, rather than the delivery model or service itself. A logic model compiled by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention would be suitable, as all processes (i.e., inputs, activities, outputs) are strictly means to the end goal. Use of this model would eliminate the focus on delivery and instead, would narrow research towards the desired impacts and outcomes of the services. This shift should especially be pursued at a time when health care is shifting from volume to value and outcome-based payments. With this in place it will be possible to assess whether telehealth is improving health care outcomes.
